Abstract

Distributed Mean Estimation (DME), in which nğ‘›n clients communicate vectors to a parameter server that estimates their average, is a fundamental building block in communication-efficient federated learning. In this paper, we improve on previous DME techniques that achieve the optimal Oâ€‹(1/n)ğ‘‚1ğ‘›O(1/n) Normalized Mean Squared Error (NMSE) guarantee by asymptotically improving the complexity for either encoding or decoding (or both). To achieve this, we formalize the problem in a novel way that allows us to use off-the-shelf mathematical solvers to design the quantization.

1 Introduction

Federated learningÂ McMahan etÂ al. (2017); Kairouz etÂ al. (2019), is a technique to train models across multiple clients without having to share their data. During each training round, the participating clients send their model updates (hereafter referred to as gradients) to a parameter server that calculates their mean and updates the model for the next round. Collecting the gradients from the participating clients is often communication-intensive, which implies that the network becomes a bottleneck. Thus, many works focus on reducing communication overheads utilizing compression. Typically, the clients reduce bandwidth by sending compact approximations of their gradients, which implies that the parameter server only achieves an approximation of the mean. Such methods offer tradeoffs between the required bandwidth, computational efficiency, and estimation accuracy.

Formally, the Distributed Mean Estimation (DME) problem is defined as follows. Consider nğ‘›n clients with dğ‘‘d-dimensional vectors (e.g., gradients) to report; each client sends an approximation of its vector to a parameter server (hereafter referred to as â€˜serverâ€™) which estimates the vectorsâ€™ mean, e.g., see Suresh etÂ al. Common to these techniques is that they preprocess the input vectors into a different representation that allows for better lossy compression, generally through quantization of the coordinates.

For example, inÂ Suresh etÂ al. 3.1 Design Goals

We aim to develop a DME technique that requires less computational overhead while achieving the same accuracy at the same compression level as the best previous techniques.

As shown by recent works Suresh etÂ al. (2017); Lyubarskii & Vershynin (2010); Caldas etÂ al. (2018); Safaryan etÂ al. (2020); Vargaftik etÂ al. (2021, 2022), a preprocessing stage that transforms each clientâ€™s vector to a vector with a different distribution (such as applying a uniform random rotation or RHT) can lead to smaller quantization errors and asymptotically lower ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE}. However, in existing DME techniques that achieve the asymptotically optimal ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} of Oâ€‹(1/n)ğ‘‚1ğ‘›O(1/n), such preprocessing incurs a high computational overhead on either the clients (i.e., Lyubarskii & Vershynin (2010); Caldas etÂ al. (2018); Safaryan etÂ al. (2020)) or the server (i.e., Lyubarskii & Vershynin (2010); Caldas etÂ al. (2018); Safaryan etÂ al. (2020); Vargaftik etÂ al. (2021, 2022)). The question is then how to preserve the appealing ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} of Oâ€‹(1/n)ğ‘‚1ğ‘›O({1}/{n}) but reduce the computational burden?

In QUIC-FL, similarly to previous DME techniques, we use a preprocessing stage111For simplicity, we first consider a uniform random rotation and then, in SectionÂ 3.5, move to the computationally efficient RHT instead, while preserving the guarantees specified inÂ TableÂ 1. where each client applies a uniform random rotation on its input vector. We use our knowledge of the resulting distribution to devise a fast and near-optimal unbiased quantization scheme that both preserves the appealing Oâ€‹(1/n)ğ‘‚1ğ‘›O(1/n) ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} guarantee and is asymptotically faster than existing DME techniques with similar ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} guarantees. 3.2 Bounded support quantization

Our first contribution is the introduction of bounded support quantization (BSQ). For a parameter pâˆˆ(0,1]ğ‘01p\in(0,1], we pick a threshold tpsubscriptğ‘¡ğ‘t_{p} such that up to dâ‹…pâ‹…ğ‘‘ğ‘d\cdot p values can fall outside [âˆ’tp,tp]subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘[-t_{p},t_{p}]. BSQ separates the vector into two parts: the small values in the range [âˆ’tp,tp]subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘[-t_{p},t_{p}], and the remaining (large) values. The large values are sent exactly (matching the precision of the input), whereas the small values are stochastically quantized and sent using a small number of bits each. This approach decreases the error of the quantized values by bounding their support at the cost of sending a small number of values exactly.

For the exactly sent values, we also need to send their indices. There are different ways to do so. For example, it is possible to encode these indices using logâ¡(ddâ‹…p)â‰ˆdâ‹…pâ‹…logâ¡(1/p)binomialğ‘‘â‹…ğ‘‘ğ‘â‹…ğ‘‘ğ‘1ğ‘\log{\binom{d}{d\cdot p}}\approx d\cdot p\cdot\log(1/p) bits at the cost of higher complexity. Empirically, sending the indices using âŒˆlogâ¡dâŒ‰ğ‘‘\lceil\log d\rceil bits each without encoding is most useful, as pâ‹…logâ¡dâ‰ª1much-less-thanâ‹…ğ‘ğ‘‘1p\cdot\log d\ll 1 in our settings, resulting in fast processing time and small bandwidth overhead.

3.3 Distribution-aware unbiased quantization

The first step towards our goal involves randomly rotating and scaling an input vector and then using BSQ to send values (rotated and scaled coordinates) outside the range [âˆ’tp,tp]subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘[-t_{p},t_{p}] exactly. The values in the range [âˆ’tp,tp]subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘[-t_{p},t_{p}] are sent using stochastic quantization, which ensures unbiasedness for any choice of quantization-values that cover that range. Now we seek quantization-values that minimize the estimation variance and thereby the ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE}. We take advantage of the fact that, after randomly rotating a vector xÂ¯âˆˆâ„dÂ¯ğ‘¥superscriptâ„ğ‘‘\overline{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{d} and scaling it by d/âˆ¥xÂ¯âˆ¥2ğ‘‘subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥Â¯ğ‘¥2\sqrt{d}/\left\lVert\overline{x}\right\rVert_{2}, the rotated and scaled coordinates approach the distribution of independent normal random variables ğ’©â€‹(0,1)ğ’©01\mathcal{N}(0,1) as dğ‘‘d increasesÂ Vargaftik etÂ al. 3.4 Putting it all together

The pseudo-code of QUIC-FL appears in AlgorithmÂ 1. As mentioned, we use the uniform random rotation as a preprocessing stage done by the clients. Crucially, similarly toÂ Suresh etÂ al. Accelerating QUIC-FL with RHT.

Similarly to previous algorithms that use random rotations as a preprocessing state (e.g.,Â Suresh etÂ al. (2017); Vargaftik etÂ al. Although RHT does not induce a uniform distribution on the sphere, it is considerably more efficient to compute, and, under mild assumptions, the resulting distribution is close to that of a uniform random rotationÂ Vargaftik etÂ al. (2021). Nevertheless, we are interested in establishing how using RHT instead of a uniform random rotation affects the formal guarantees of QUIC-FL.

5 Related Works

In SectionÂ 1, we gave an overview of most related compression (DME) methods. Here we focus on specific sub-topics. We further review other techniques in AppendixÂ A.

Bounded support quantization. Previous works on compression in federated learning observed considered bounding the range of the updates. They suggest ad-hoc mitigations, such as clipping Zhang etÂ al. (2020); Wen etÂ al. (2017); Zhang etÂ al. (2022); Charles etÂ al. (2021), preconditioning Suresh etÂ al. (2017); Caldas etÂ al. (2018), and bucketing Alistarh etÂ al. (2017). On the other hand, methods such as Top-kğ‘˜k Stich etÂ al. (2018a); Sinha etÂ al. (2020) demonstrate that considering the largest coordinates is advantageous. HorvÃ¡th & Richtarik (2021) provides convergence guarantees from combining biased and unbiased compressed estimators. BSQ similarly tries to benefit by sending the largest transformed coordinates exactly while sending the rest via unbiased compression.

Distribution-aware quantization. Quantization over a distribution, and over a Gaussian source in particular, has been studied for almost a century (for a comprehensive overview, we refer to Gray & Neuhoff (1998)). Nevertheless, to our knowledge, such research has not focused on the unbiasedness constraint. The only comparable methods that we are aware of are based on stochastic quantization and introduce an error that increases with the vectorâ€™s dimension. There are additional unbiased methods that use shared randomness (e.g., Roberts (1962a); BenÂ Basat etÂ al. (2021)), but again, we are unaware of any work that directly optimizes quantization for a distribution with an unbiasedness constraint. As previously mentioned, perhaps the closest to our approach is the Lloyd-Max Scalar QuantizerÂ Lloyd (1982); Max (1960), which optimizes the mean squared error without unbiasedness constraints. Interestingly, there are many generalizations to Lloyd-Max, such as vector quantization Linde etÂ al. (1980) methods and lattice quantization Gersho (1979). In future work, we plan to investigate these approaches and extend our distribution-aware unbiasedness quantization framework accordingly.

Appendix A Extended Related Work

This paper focused on the Distributed Mean Estimation (DME) problem where clients send lossily compressed vectors to a centralized server for averaging. While this problem is worthy of study on its own merits, we are particularly interested in applications to federated learning, where there are many variations and practical considerations, which have led to many alternative compression methods to be considered.

We note that in essence, QUIC-FL is a compression scheme. However, unlike previous DME approaches such as Suresh etÂ al. (2017); Vargaftik etÂ al. (2021, 2022), it brings benefits only in a distributed setting with multiple clients, distinguishing it from standard vector quantization methods.

Frameworks that use DME as a building block.

In addition to EF21Â RichtÃ¡rik etÂ al. (2021) and MARINAÂ Gorbunov etÂ al. (2021); Szlendak etÂ al. (2022) which are discussed in detail below, there are additional frameworks that leverage DME as a building block. For example, EF-BVÂ Condat etÂ al. (2022b), Qsparse-local-SGDÂ Basu etÂ al. (2019), 3PCÂ RichtÃ¡rik etÂ al. (2022), CompressedScaffnewÂ Condat etÂ al. (2022a), MURANAÂ Condat & RichtÃ¡rik (2022), and DIANAÂ HorvÃ¡th etÂ al. (2023) accelerate the convergence of non-convex learning tasks via variance reduction, control variates, and compression. These approaches are orthogonal and can benefit from better DME techniques such as QUIC-FL.

Entropy encoding.

When the encoding and decoding time is less important, some previous approaches have suggested using an entropy encoding such as Huffman or arithmetic encoding to improve the accuracy (e.g.,Â Alistarh etÂ al. (2017); Suresh etÂ al. (2017); Vargaftik etÂ al. (2022); Dorfman etÂ al. (2023)). Intuitively, such encodings allow us to losslessly compress the lossily compressed vector to reduce its representation size, thereby allowing less aggressive quantization. However, we are unaware of available GPU-friendly entropy encoding implementation and thus such methods incur a significant time overhead.

Client-side memory.

Critically, for the basic DME problem, the assumption is that this is a one-shot process where the goal is to optimize the accuracy without relying on client-side memory. This model naturally fits cross-device federated learning, where different clients are sampled in each round. We focused on unbiased compression, which is standard in prior worksÂ Suresh etÂ al. (2017); KoneÄná»³ & RichtÃ¡rik (2018); Vargaftik etÂ al. (2021); Davies etÂ al. (2021); Mitchell etÂ al. (2022). However, if the compression error is low enough, and under some assumptions, SGD can be proven to converge even with biased compressionÂ Beznosikov etÂ al. (2020).

Error feedback.

In other settings, such as distributed learning or cross-silo federated learning, we may assume that clients are persistent and have a memory that keeps state between rounds. A prominent option to leverage such a state is to use Error Feedback (EF). In EF, clients can track the compression error and add it to the vector computed in the consecutive round. This scheme is often shown to recover the modelâ€™s convergence rate and resulting accuracyÂ Seide etÂ al. (2014); Alistarh etÂ al. (2018); RichtÃ¡rik etÂ al. (2021); Karimireddy etÂ al. (2019) and enables biased compressors such as Top-kğ‘˜kÂ Stich etÂ al. (2018a) and SignSGDÂ Bernstein etÂ al. (2018). We compare with the state of the art technique, EF21Â RichtÃ¡rik etÂ al. (2021), in addition to showing how it can be used in conjunction with QUIC-FL to facilitate further improvement in AppendixÂ G.

Gradient differences.

An orthogonal proposal that works with persistent clients, which is also applicable with QUIC-FL, is to encode the difference between the current vector and the previous one instead of directly compressing the vectorÂ Mishchenko etÂ al. (2019); Gorbunov etÂ al. (2021). Broadly speaking, this allows a compression error proportional to the L2 norm of the difference and not the vector and can decrease the error if consecutive vectors are similar to each other.

In-network aggregation.

When running distributed learning in cluster settings, recent works show how in-network aggregation can accelerate the learning processÂ Sapio etÂ al. (2021); Lao etÂ al. (2021); Segal etÂ al. (2021); Li etÂ al. (2023). IntSGDÂ Mishchenko etÂ al. (2022) is another compression scheme that allows one to aggregate the compressed integer vectors in the network. However, their solution may require sending 141414 bits per coordinate while we consider 1âˆ’5151-5 bits per coordinate in QUIC-FL. Intuitively, switches are designed to move data at high speeds, and recent advances in switch programmability enable them to easily perform simple aggregation operations like summation while processing the data. Extending QUIC-FL to allow efficient in-network aggregation is left as future work.

Sparsification.

Another line of work focuses on sparsifying the vectors before compressing themÂ KoneÄnÃ½ etÂ al. (2017); Aji & Heafield (2017); KoneÄná»³ & RichtÃ¡rik (2018); Wangni etÂ al. (2018); Stich etÂ al. (2018b); Fei etÂ al. (2021); Vargaftik etÂ al. (2022). Intuitively, in some learning settings, many of the coordinates are small, and we can improve the accuracy to bandwidth tradeoff by removing all small coordinates prior to compression. Another form of sparsification is random sampling, which allows us to avoid sending the coordinate indicesÂ KoneÄnÃ½ etÂ al. (2017); Vargaftik etÂ al. (2022). We note that combining such approaches with QUIC-FL is straightforward, as we can use QUIC-FL to compress just the non-zero entries of the sparsified vectors.

Deep gradient compression.

By combining techniques like warm-up training, vector clipping, momentum factor masking, momentum correction, and deep vector compression, Lin etÂ al. (2018) reports savings of two orders of magnitude in the bandwidth required for distributed learning.

As shown inÂ BenÂ Basat etÂ al. (2021), shared randomness can reduce the worst-case error of quantizing a single [0,1]01[0,1] value both in biased and unbiased settings. The QUIC-FL algorithm, based on the output of the solver (see Â§3), uses non-uniform quantization, i.e., has quantization levels that are not uniformly spaced. G.3 Distributed Power Iteration

We simulate 101010 clients that distributively compute the top eigenvector in a matrix (i.e., the matrix rows are distributed among the clients). Particularly, each client executes a power iteration, compresses its top eigenvector, and sends it to the server. The server updates the next estimated eigenvector by the averaged diffs (of each client to the eigenvector from the previous round) and scales it by a learning rate of 0.10.10.1. Then, the estimated eigenvector is sent by the server to the clients and the next round can begin.

FigureÂ 10 presents the L2 error of the obtained eigenvector by each compression scheme when compared to the eigenvector that is achieved without compression. The results cover bit budget bğ‘b from one bit to four bits for both MNIST and CIFAR-10Â Krizhevsky etÂ al. (2009); LeCun etÂ al. (1998, 2010) datasets. Each distributed power iteration simulation is executed for 50 rounds for the MNIST dataset and for 200 rounds for the CIFAR-10 dataset.

As shown, QUIC-FL has an accuracy that is competitive with that of EDEN (especially for bâ‰¥2ğ‘2b\geq 2) while having asymptotically faster decoding, as EDEN requires decompressing the vector for each client independently. At the same time, QUIC-FL is considerably better in terms of accuracy than other algorithms that offer fast decoding time. Also, Kashin-TF is not unbiased (as illustrated by FigureÂ 2), and is, therefore, less competitive for a larger number of clients.

We compare QUIC-FL with Sparse Dithering (SD)Â Albasyoni etÂ al. (2020).
